{{wikipedia|Vocative case}}

===Etymology===
From Late {{inh|en|enm}}, borrowed from {{bor|en|frm|vocatif}}, from {{der|en|la|vocātīvus||for calling}}; a calque of Ancient Greek {{m|grc|κλητῐκή||for calling; vocative case}} &ndash; from {{m|la|voco|vocāre|to call}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro||*wokʷ-}}, [[o-grade]] of {{m|ine-pro|*wekʷ-|t=give vocal utterance, speak}}. See Latin {{m|la|vōx}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|en|/ˈvɑkətɪv/}}
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/ˈvɒkətɪv/}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Of or pertaining to calling; used in calling or [[vocation]].
# {{lb|en|grammar}} Used in address; [[appellative]] (said of that case or form of the noun, pronoun, or adjective, in which a person or thing is addressed). For example "''Domine'', O Lord"

